{
	"appId": "69a04458c2f6d3e098135b38",



	"year": "1469",	


	"longDescription": "THE BIRTH OF GURU NANAK - Guru Nanak (1469-1539), the first of the ten Gurus of the Sikhs, was born in Nankana Sahib near Lahore to a Hindu merchant (Khatri) family and he amazed those around him with his spiritual insight from childhood. Nanak questioned the status quo, starting with the rituals the family priest wanted him to follow, his teacher's instructions and the injustices he saw in society. He rejected all distinctions of religion, caste, and gender – seeking solitude in devotion and serving the poor. The story of the Sachā Saudā, the True Investment, is emblematic of Nanak’s mindset. When Nanak was 18 years old, his father gave him twenty rupees to go to the city and buy some goods that he could trade to make a profitable investment. But the young Guru used that money to buy food and clothes for the poor. Upon returning home the Guru explained to his father that helping others was the True Investment. He institutionalized this sentiment later as langar, or free communal kitchens, that are present in Gurdwaras (Sikh Temple) worldwide"

	
}

